=Discussion=

Allen Butcher:

"The processes of creating and maintaining time-based, non-monetary economics is named by this author, “intentioneering,” a term which combines the ideas of intentional community and of behavioral engineering to represent the method that people have used since monetary economics was first invented sometime before 3,000 B.C. to escape monetary economics.  Ever since then people have resisted the monetary system, using every method they can think of to step outside of monetary economics, including “back-to-the-land” and “voluntary simplicity” and “neo-tribal” as well as intentional community movements.

 

Communal society, in particular, results in nearly complete non-monetary cultures, creating community-owned businesses to make money, which is then communally used to support the members.  This income is not distributed to members in return for their labor, instead it is budgeted to cover community expenses, although the members do typically agree to give themselves a small personal allowance or discretionary fund for which to pay for things that the community does not budget.  Community-owned businesses are different from worker-owned businesses because even those community members who do not work in the community business benefit from the income derived from them.  For this a participatory decision-making process is used rather than any form of authoritarianism, in order to create and support an egalitarian culture.

 

While there are many different forms of intentional community, the whole diverse field can be understood by considering the difference between labor-gifting and labor-sharing.  The former, labor-gifting, involves people donating their time to their community, with no minimum labor requirement.  In these communities, like cohousing, people pay their own way such as by purchasing their living-unit along with a portion of the common facilities (and also like community land trusts where people build their own housing on community-owned land), and although they are expected to help with community work to some degree, they cannot be forced to sell and move if they do not work.

 

In contrast, intentional communities which use labor-sharing have a minimum labor requirement in order for people to maintain their membership.  If members of a labor-sharing community or communal society do not contribute their share of labor, as set by the community as a number of hours per week in the form of a “labor quota,” their membership may be revoked and the person would have to leave the community.  This is essentially what St. Paul was saying when he wrote to the Early Christian Church at Thessalonica in Macedonia in 50 A.D. that, “those who do not work shall not eat.” [II Thessalonians 3:10]  This is a classic communal dictum which shows that many early Christian churches were to some degree communal.  St. Paul’s statement is a tenet of labor-sharing, which is very different from labor-gifting communities requiring instead only that people pay a minimum amount of money earned from jobs or careers outside of the community.

 

While spirituality and religion can be powerful motivating factors for people to step outside of the monetary system into community, the economic processes are the same for spiritual/religious as for secular intentional communities.  Either type can be authoritarian or egalitarian, while it is in the latter that fairness and justice for all are mandated in the written agreements that members typically sign upon joining.

 

All forms of intentional community essentially exploit capitalism in order to build their alternative society, simply because the monetary system is the medium we swim in every day.  Building intentional community creates time-based economic bubbles within the sea of monetary economics, each one expanding and contracting as people join and leave the community.  Yet the monetary system will continue to exist through the future regardless of communitarian movements, and so the need is to learn how to manipulate a force which typically destroys community, to instead intentioneer it to create community, by people working together in exploiting capitalism!"
(http://0350f21.netsolhost.com/WordPress/2013/09/28/exploit-capitalism-to-build-gifting-and-sharing-lifestyles/)


